title>Exploring empowerment in rural Uganda: young people, sexual health and NGOs</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Fellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>ES/I015868/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>Concepts of 'empowerment have been widely used In discussions of how best to reduce young people's vulnerability to HIV and other sexual health problems. Concurrently, the increasingly thetorical use of 'empowemenf by diverse development institutions has been heavily criticised. Drawing on evidence from empirical research in Uganda, this Post-Doctoral Fellowship will provide a unique opportunity to strengthen understanding of youth empowerment by:&lt;/p>

&lt;ul>
 

 &lt;li>Examining meanings of personal, relational and contextual empowerment in relation to young people and their sexual health. Within public health, empowerment is often understood as enhancing individual control over decision-makingand action. Publications will challenge this assumption, highlighting the mediating effects of social values and&amp;nbsp; livelihood insecurity on young people's sexual lives.&lt;/li>

 &lt;li>Contributing a generational dimension to existing gender-based analyses of empowerment. Publications will develop understanding of the links between personal and relational dimensions of empowerment, revealing to policy makers and practitioners that whilst young people can develop a clear sense of personal empowerment (eg knowledge, life skills), relationships with people of different ages influence behaviours and impact sexual health outcomes.&lt;/li>

 &lt;li>Strengthening understanding of the transformative role of NGOs in multisectoral approaches to HIV prevention in developing countries. Publications will provide insight into NGOs' grassroots sexual health work revealing important future challenges including: changing young people's relationships with adutt gatekeepers who influence sexual behaviours; tackling wider social norms and economic circumstances influencing young people's sexual health; using a more sophisticated understanding of empowerment to design programmes and evaluation to illuminate complex&lt;br />processes at work.&lt;/li>

&lt;/ul></gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2011-12-31</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE"><gtr:id>924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE</gtr:id><gtr:name>ESRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2011-01-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>87948</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs/><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs/><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications/><gtr:identifiers><gtr:identifier type="RCUK">ES/I015868/1</gtr:identifier></gtr:identifiers><gtr:healthCategories/><gtr:researchActivities/><gtr:researchSubjects><gtr:researchSubject><gtr:id>64564C94-AC7F-4056-903D-0AED107A359E</gtr:id><gtr:percentage>0</gtr:percentage><gtr:text>Education</gtr:text></gtr:researchSubject><gtr:researchSubject><gtr:id>12179D88-04B3-47E9-89E1-B5EE8F895227</gtr:id><gtr:percentage>0</gtr:percentage><gtr:text>Social Policy</gtr:text></gtr:researchSubject></gtr:researchSubjects><gtr:researchTopics><gtr:researchTopic><gtr:id>64564C94-AC7F-4056-903D-0AED107A359E</gtr:id><gtr:percentage>0</gtr:percentage><gtr:text>Education</gtr:text></gtr:researchTopic><gtr:researchTopic><gtr:id>12179D88-04B3-47E9-89E1-B5EE8F895227</gtr:id><gtr:percentage>0</gtr:percentage><gtr:text>Social Policy</gtr:text></gtr:researchTopic></gtr:researchTopics><gtr:rcukProgrammes/></gtr:project></gtr:projectComposition></gtr:projectOverview>